"The first is, that an air of piety upon all occa- sions should be maintained in the whole poem. \"This appears in all the ancient Greek writers, as Homer, Hesiod, Aratus, &c. And Virgil is so exact in the observation of it, (not only in this work, but in his /Eneis too,) that a celebrated French writer taxes him for permitting ZAineas to do nothing without the assistance of some god. But by this it appears, at least, that M. St. Evre- mont is no Jansenist,"